{"id": "12580", "revid": "43671602", "url": "https://divinity.fandom.com/wiki?curid=12580", "title": "Divine Divinity Characters", "text": "Divine Divinity's non-player characters are each one of seven &lt;a href=\"race\"&gt;race&lt;/a&gt;s: &lt;a href=\"dwarf\"&gt;dwarf&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"elf\"&gt;elf&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"human\"&gt;human&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"imp\"&gt;imp&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"lizard\"&gt;lizard&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"orc\"&gt;orc&lt;/a&gt; and the &lt;a href=\"undead\"&gt;undead&lt;/a&gt;."}
{"id": "19385", "revid": "43671602", "url": "https://divinity.fandom.com/wiki?curid=19385", "title": "Divine Divinity Charms", "text": " are a type of &lt;a href=\"Divine%20Divinity%20miscellaneous%20items\"&gt;miscellaneous item&lt;/a&gt; in \"&lt;a href=\"Divine%20Divinity\"&gt;Divine Divinity&lt;/a&gt;\"\nCharacteristics.\nThey are magical orbs which can be inserted into equipment with a sufficiently high enough &lt;a href=\"Enchant%20Weapon\"&gt;Enchant Weapon&lt;/a&gt; skill. Depending on the specific charms inserted the stats of the item in question will be improved. There are also non-linearities with charm values: less potent versions might be more expensive than more powerful versions.\nAgility.\nMistakenly labeled to increase Dexterity."}
{"id": "11461", "revid": "53418829", "url": "https://divinity.fandom.com/wiki?curid=11461", "title": "Divine Divinity Classes", "text": "Classes in \"&lt;a href=\"Divine%20Divinity\"&gt;Divine Divinity&lt;/a&gt;\" set &lt;a href=\"Lucian\"&gt;Lucian&lt;/a&gt;'s starting traits. One can choose from the &lt;a href=\"warrior\"&gt;warrior&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"mage\"&gt;mage&lt;/a&gt; or &lt;a href=\"survivor\"&gt;survivor&lt;/a&gt;. \nOverview.\nOn starting a new game, both the class and gender can be selected. The impact of gender affects starting &lt;a href=\"Divine%20Divinity%20Skills\"&gt;skills&lt;/a&gt; only, the class defines the special skill for the character and cannot be changed:\nWarriors value physical strength over speed or magical ability. Their special skill is a whirlwind attack which will cause physical damage to all those in range. \nMages place emphasis on magical prowess, attempting to avoid direct physical combat. Their special skill allows them to teleport to the mouse cursor's location.\nSurvivors are interested in self preservation and their skills are reflective of this. Their special skill allows them to cloak when in shadows.\nIn addition to the special skill, the derived statistics of &lt;a href=\"offence\"&gt;offence&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"defence\"&gt;defence&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"mana\"&gt;mana&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"vitality\"&gt;vitality&lt;/a&gt; will differ as core attributes are increased.\nThese three classes should be considered a starting point, the player is not bound to develop their character specifically on the path of the chosen class: when levelling up or obtaining skill books it is possible to learn skills from the other three classes."}
{"id": "14825", "revid": "49426621", "url": "https://divinity.fandom.com/wiki?curid=14825", "title": "Divine Divinity Consumables", "text": "Consumables are single use items which typically grant the user a temporary effect. Consuming multiple items will cause the effects to run simultaneously, note that if these effects cumulatively bring one's &lt;a href=\"Intelligence\"&gt;Intelligence&lt;/a&gt; to or below 0 all equipment will be rendered unusable.\nConsumables can be broken down into food, drink and potions.\nFood.\nFruits can be combined with various containers to change their value and/or weight properties. In some cases, the container variant is weightless, but to make encumbrance display correctly, the container must first be dropped for the change to show.\n&lt;dpl&gt;\ncategory=Divine Divinity consumables\nuses=Template:Infobox consumable\nincludepage={Infobox consumable}:type:effects:weight:value\ntable=class=\"article-table sortable\",Name,Type,Effects,Weight,Value\n&lt;/dpl&gt;"}
{"id": "14786", "revid": "49426621", "url": "https://divinity.fandom.com/wiki?curid=14786", "title": "Divine Divinity Creatures", "text": "In \"&lt;a href=\"Divine%20Divinity\"&gt;Divine Divinity&lt;/a&gt;\" creatures act as both scene dressing and opponents/obstacles. All creatures can be killed and will provide &lt;a href=\"experience\"&gt;experience&lt;/a&gt; upon death. Experience gained drops as &lt;a href=\"Lucian\"&gt;Lucian&lt;/a&gt; gains levels.\nAnimals.\nIn most cases, animals are identical to their real world counterparts in description and behaviour. The only exception to this are spiders and scorpions who have been enlarged.\nUndead.\nRaised from their graves to act at the bidding of a master or by some other form of necromancy, the undead are often found at the site of tombs or graveyards, rarely straying from these areas."}
{"id": "20848", "revid": "43671602", "url": "https://divinity.fandom.com/wiki?curid=20848", "title": "Divine Divinity Guides", "text": " is a page containing guides and explanations to all key aspects of the &lt;a href=\"Divine%20Divinity\"&gt;Divine Divinity&lt;/a&gt; game. \nDescription.\nDivine Divinity is a single-player, rpg game and the first game in the &lt;a href=\"Series\"&gt;Divinity Series&lt;/a&gt;. The game was first released in 2002 and later in 2012, alongside &lt;a href=\"Beyond%20Divinity\"&gt;Beyond Divinity&lt;/a&gt; and , added into the Divinity Anthology bundle during 10th year Divinity anniversary. In the game the player takes the role of a &lt;a href=\"Marked%20Ones\"&gt;Marked One&lt;/a&gt;, a &lt;a href=\"Humans\"&gt;human&lt;/a&gt; chosen by the Divine Being to become the Divine One. The game was accompanied by the &lt;a href=\"The%20Prophecy\"&gt;Prophecy&lt;/a&gt; novella which provided some background to the in-game story.\nUser Guides.\nFollowing guides are mostly solo user created content, tailored to specific topics. The responsibility for corretness of the information falls under the users themselves. The management of the pages falls under the user who made them. "}
{"id": "17827", "revid": "49426621", "url": "https://divinity.fandom.com/wiki?curid=17827", "title": "Divine Divinity Locations", "text": "Divine Divinity consists of four regions: &lt;a href=\"Ferol\"&gt;Ferol&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"The%20Dark%20Forest\"&gt;The Dark Forest&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Verdistis\"&gt;Verdistis&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Yuthul%20Gor\"&gt;Yuthul Gor&lt;/a&gt;.\nFerol.\nFerol is the first region encountered when &lt;a href=\"Lucian\"&gt;Lucian&lt;/a&gt; wakes up in the basement of &lt;a href=\"Joram\"&gt;Joram&lt;/a&gt;'s home in &lt;a href=\"Aleroth\"&gt;Aleroth&lt;/a&gt;. &lt;a href=\"Rivertown\"&gt;Rivertown&lt;/a&gt; dominates the region with &lt;a href=\"Stormfist%20Castle\"&gt;Stormfist Castle&lt;/a&gt; at its epicentre; the &lt;a href=\"Rivertown%20Watch\"&gt;Rivertown Watch&lt;/a&gt; operating outside the castle's entrance on the south side. On its eastern side is the &lt;a href=\"Church\"&gt;Church&lt;/a&gt; (far north), &lt;a href=\"cursed%20abbey\"&gt;cursed abbey&lt;/a&gt; (mid north), &lt;a href=\"The%20Farmlands\"&gt;The Farmlands&lt;/a&gt; and the &lt;a href=\"Blue%20Boar%20Inn\"&gt;Blue Boar Inn&lt;/a&gt; (due east), and the town's &lt;a href=\"poor%20area\"&gt;poor area&lt;/a&gt; (south).\nDirectly south is the &lt;a href=\"Rivertown%20Watch\"&gt;Rivertown Watch&lt;/a&gt; and south west the famed &lt;a href=\"Dwarven%20Bread%20Inn\"&gt;Dwarven Bread Inn&lt;/a&gt;. Due north of the castle is &lt;a href=\"Nericon%27s%20Garden\"&gt;Nericon's Garden&lt;/a&gt; and further north (to the west of the church) is the town's main graveyard; its &lt;a href=\"pauper%27s%20graveyard\"&gt;pauper's graveyard&lt;/a&gt; lies south of the poor quarter. To the north east is the town's &lt;a href=\"Rivertown%20Market\"&gt;market&lt;/a&gt; and the road to &lt;a href=\"Verdistis\"&gt;Verdistis&lt;/a&gt;. On the southern boundary of the town lies its &lt;a href=\"army%20barracks\"&gt;army barracks&lt;/a&gt;.\nDue east of the castle is &lt;a href=\"dwarven\"&gt;dwarven&lt;/a&gt; territory, with the dwarven village of &lt;a href=\"Glenborus\"&gt;Glenborus&lt;/a&gt; and the &lt;a href=\"dwarven%20forest\"&gt;dwarven forest&lt;/a&gt; on its easternmost boundary.\nSouth of the town is a battleground between the &lt;a href=\"orcs\"&gt;orcs&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"humans\"&gt;humans&lt;/a&gt;, with the humans holding the line at the &lt;a href=\"destroyed%20village\"&gt;destroyed village&lt;/a&gt;, with an additional &lt;a href=\"camp\"&gt;supply camp&lt;/a&gt; to the east of the village. The south east is dominated by the &lt;a href=\"orc%20camp\"&gt;orc camp&lt;/a&gt; and the south east road leads to the &lt;a href=\"Archer%27s%20Guild%20%28building%29\"&gt;Archer's Guild&lt;/a&gt;, the elven lands and a &lt;a href=\"Arnie%27s%20house\"&gt;Arnie's house&lt;/a&gt; across the road from it.\nThere are also several caves in the region: \nVerdistis.\nThe walled city of Ferol, &lt;a href=\"Verdistis\"&gt;Verdistis&lt;/a&gt;, is the home of the rich nobles. The city is walled in on all sides with a single gate to the south. The west side of the town is dedicated to merchants and entertainment and the east to the homes of the residents themselves."}
{"id": "14824", "revid": "49426621", "url": "https://divinity.fandom.com/wiki?curid=14824", "title": "Divine Divinity Miscellaneous Items", "text": "Miscellaneous items are objects that do not provide any direct use nor fall into any specific category (&lt;a href=\"Divine%20Divinity%20Armour\"&gt;armour&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Divine%20Divinity%20Weapons\"&gt;weapons&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Divine%20Divinity%20books%20and%20notes\"&gt;books&lt;/a&gt;, or &lt;a href=\"Divine%20Divinity%20Consumables\"&gt;consumables&lt;/a&gt;). The type of items that fall into the category of miscellaneous are broad, from herbs like &lt;a href=\"augmentor\"&gt;augmentor&lt;/a&gt; to containers such as &lt;a href=\"barrel\"&gt;barrel&lt;/a&gt;s.\n&lt;dpl&gt;\ncategory=Divine Divinity miscellaneous items\nuses =Template:Infobox item\nincludepage = {Infobox item}:value:weight\ntable = class=\"article-table sortable\",Name,Value,Weight\n&lt;/dpl&gt;"}
{"id": "18807", "revid": "43671602", "url": "https://divinity.fandom.com/wiki?curid=18807", "title": "Divine Divinity Music", "text": "Music for the first game in the Divinity &lt;a href=\"series\"&gt;series&lt;/a&gt; known as &lt;a href=\"Divine%20Divinity\"&gt;Divine Divinity&lt;/a&gt; was composed by Kirill Pokrovsky. \nDescription.\nThe official soundtrack contains 45 pieces including 3 tracks cut from the game. Namely: \"Bitva\", \"Old Rivertown\" and \"Against Doom and Despair\". The soundtrack used to be free on Kirill Pokrovsky's own website till it was shut-down in 2023. Some of these tracks were reused in &lt;a href=\"Beyond%20Divinity\"&gt;Beyond Divinity&lt;/a&gt; and served as base for newer music in . Most notable out of these is the main menu theme \"Divine Divinity\" which can be heard played on piano by a ghost NPC in &lt;a href=\"Ryker%27s%20Rest\"&gt;Ryker's Rest&lt;/a&gt; in \"\" game.\nSoundtracks Warrior (ru. Voin), Divine Divinity (title track), War and Peace, Desert Fight, Forest, Demona's Run and Bitva were the first songs to be made public under the courtesy of &lt;a href=\"Larian%20Studios\"&gt;Larian Studios&lt;/a&gt; themselves. Later on full soundtrack of the game was made public. Out of these only \"Demona's Run\" was never part of the official album. \nTrack List.\nUnofficial.\nFollowing soundtracks are not part of the official album and can be found only in the game itself or on older version of the composers website. Desert Fight is a longer variant of Warring Winds and Crimision Tides. Forest is a longer version of A Wind of Aleroth with background sounds. "}
{"id": "14769", "revid": "49426621", "url": "https://divinity.fandom.com/wiki?curid=14769", "title": "Divine Divinity Quest Items", "text": "Quest items are objects required to continue or complete a quest. In \"&lt;a href=\"Divine%20Divinity\"&gt;Divine Divinity&lt;/a&gt;\", these items can be dropped, butmostly cannot be sold. Once dropped there is no indicator of where they have been left."}
{"id": "14728", "revid": "43671602", "url": "https://divinity.fandom.com/wiki?curid=14728", "title": "Divine Divinity Quests", "text": "Quests in \"&lt;a href=\"Divine%20Divinity\"&gt;Divine Divinity&lt;/a&gt;\" are accessed from the action bar on the bottom of the screen, via the journal.\nWithin the journal, active quests are listed with a general outline and sub objectives available upon clicking the overarching quest. Completed and failed quests are clearly marked as such and can be filtered out to show the active quests only.\nReward experience increases as &lt;a href=\"Lucian\"&gt;Lucian&lt;/a&gt;'s level increases, until reaching the maximum possible experience for the given quest. &lt;a href=\"Wisdom%20%28Divine%20Divinity%29\"&gt;Wisdom&lt;/a&gt; affects reward experience even after reaching the maximum amount."}
{"id": "14196", "revid": "43671602", "url": "https://divinity.fandom.com/wiki?curid=14196", "title": "Divine Divinity Skills", "text": "Skills are additional abilities that can be learned by &lt;a href=\"Lucian\"&gt;Lucian&lt;/a&gt; upon leveling up. Regardless of character selection at the start of \"&lt;a href=\"Divine%20Divinity\"&gt;Divine Divinity&lt;/a&gt;\", the character starts with 2 skills and is given the option to earn 1-2 points towards skills at each level. Some skills and spells can also be learnt by reading a skillbook, or as a quest reward. These cases ignore level requirement for the skill in question.\nThere are active skills that require mana to function and passive skills that don't require mana. Skills are not tied to class; even a warrior can learn mage spells.\nIn tables below;\nWay of the mage.\nMage skills focus on magic abilities of which all (except transfer power and master summoner) require mana to use. With the exception of summons, mage skills must be cast for each attack.\nPowers of Summoning.\nThis path is centered about summoning creatures and ressurecting the dead to the caster's aid. The abilities of this path also allows the caster to bolster their summoned creatures and banish them. Additionally this path offers a spell that may drain the life force of chosen enemy. \nWay of the survivor.\nSurvivor skills are more orientated towards practical use, as opposed to combat, with one path being the exception: the Path of the Divine, which holds the skills of the divine. This fourth path remains locked to &lt;a href=\"Lucian\"&gt;Lucian&lt;/a&gt; until much later in the journey.\nPath of the Thief.\nThis path focuses on traditional thief skills; sneaking, stealing, trapping.\nPath of the Divine.\nUnlike other skill paths, the Path of the Divine is only available after Lucian receives the Divine Blessing as part of the main quest &lt;a href=\"Begin%20the%20Blessing%20Ritual\"&gt;Begin the Blessing Ritual&lt;/a&gt;. Note that while it is possible to find a skillbook for the skills (example: &lt;a href=\"Heaven%27s%20Blessing%20%28Divine%20Divinity%29\"&gt;Heaven's Blessing&lt;/a&gt; sold rarely by &lt;a href=\"Kistandalius\"&gt;Kistandalius&lt;/a&gt;), Lucian will not get any skillpoints from using it before doing the ritual. Unlike skills from other paths, divine skills have no level requirements or limitations. \nWay of the warrior.\nWarrior skills focus on improving physical prowess; the more efficient use of weapons and improving physical damage.\nPath of the Specialist.\nThis path improves overall efficiency of specific &lt;a href=\"Divine%20Divinity%20weapons\"&gt;weapon&lt;/a&gt; classes. Only Spear Expertise requires &lt;a href=\"Mana\"&gt;Mana&lt;/a&gt; to function.\nPath of the Warrior's Lore.\nThe specialty of this path is the possibility of inflicting elemental damage to enemy with normal attacks."}
