{"id": "3475", "revid": "43671602", "url": "https://divinity.fandom.com/wiki?curid=3475", "title": "Dragon Knight Saga Achievements", "text": "Achievements can be earned in the PC and Xbox 360 versions of Divinity II. They are a way to extend the game's longevity and provide players with a goal to achieve. Some of the achievements are unlocked by playing until completion, while others may otherwise be &lt;a href=\"Secrets%20%28Dragon%20Knight%20Saga%29\"&gt;secrets&lt;/a&gt;.\n\"Ego Draconis\".\nThere are 41 achievements and a total of 1000 points to earn.\n\"Flames of Vengeance\".\nThere are 50 achievements with a total of 1000 points to earn."}
{"id": "2093", "revid": "43671602", "url": "https://divinity.fandom.com/wiki?curid=2093", "title": "Dragon Knight Saga Armour", "text": "Armour is a protective equipment used by &lt;a href=\"The%20Dragon%20Knight\"&gt;The Dragon Knight&lt;/a&gt; in \"\" and its subsequent versions.\nDescription.\nThere are two basic armour types in the game. \"Human armour\" which is used to protect the Dragon Knight in their human form, and \"dragon armour\" which is used to protect the Knight in their dragon form. All armour, save for the Dragon type, requires specific level requirement to be met, before it can be worn. In ' and ' an additional attribute requirements had to be met as well alongside level requirement. \nArmour is futher on characterised by its rarity. The greater rarity armour has, the greater its defensive properties may be. Below is a list of all possible equipment rarity in game:\nArmour types.\nDragon Armour.\nDragon armour is one of the few ways a Dragon Knight can protect themselves in their dragon form. There are \"4 sets of Dragon armour\" in \"Divinity II\" and it is the only armour that can be worn in the dragon form. All of these pieces are unique and unlike human armour sets, do not get additional bonuses when worn together. This means that armour pieces can be combined and worn as needed. All armour pieces have the value of 600 gold. \nHuman Armour.\nHuman armour is constituted of similar parts as the dragon: helmet, chest armour, gloves and leggings. Like dragon armour it also has differing styles, based on various factions present on Rivellon. Unlike dragon armour not all of the armour present in game is unique. Values for set armour pieces, are based on sole equipment. For armour values when wearing full set see Armour Sets section. All icons are taken from in-game files since only \"male icons\" are visible in the game, regardless of the Dragon Knights gender.\nUnlike dragon armour, human armour can be improved by charms and enchantments. Human armour also comes in much greater varieties than dragon armour. Following armour styles are all found in the game and are further separated into 3 tiers, with the exception of Noble (Dragon Lord), Champion and Guard (Mine Guard) styles which are separated into 4 tiers, with the final 4th tier being the \"Flames of Vengeance\" special armour set. \nArmour Sets.\nArmour sets are made up of separate pieces of armour, &lt;a href=\"Dragon%20Knight%20Saga%20Accessories\"&gt;jewellery&lt;/a&gt;, and &lt;a href=\"Dragon%20Knight%20Saga%20Weapons\"&gt;weapons&lt;/a&gt; with the same names. Each item has its own individual attributes, but secondary skill and attribute boosts are attached based on the number of pieces from the set being worn.\nThere are several unique armour sets in Divinity II game which provide defensive bonuses depending on how many pieces of the set are worn. Set pieces are exclusive to the part of the game they are in, meaning that there are no set items scattered across both \"Divinity II: Ego Draconis\" and \"Divinity II: Flames of Vengeance\" DLC. The bonuses are calculated based on the percentage of the set pieces worn. Differing sets have different amount of armour, weaponry and accessories as part of it. Following tables show bonuses provided only by armour pieces in the set. \nFlames of Vengeance Sets.\nFollowing set are always made of five pieces: helmet, cuirass, gloves, leggings and one accessory. "}
{"id": "2233", "revid": "27868532", "url": "https://divinity.fandom.com/wiki?curid=2233", "title": "Dragon Knight Saga Books and Notes", "text": "The world of &lt;a href=\"Rivellon\"&gt;Rivellon&lt;/a&gt; is filled with lots of books. Some of them are used in &lt;a href=\"quests\"&gt;quests&lt;/a&gt;, others can be used directly to get stats or &lt;a href=\"Skills%20%28Dragon%20Knight%20Saga%29\"&gt;skill&lt;/a&gt; points. Most of them just have information about history, personal events or feelings etc. Some books are also part of quests, provide hints for secrets or may be used to improve &lt;a href=\"The%20Dragon%20Knight\"&gt;the Knights&lt;/a&gt; stats and skills.\nYou can sell books for some gold, but don't expect to get rich that way. On the other hand, books are heavy and increase your load weight by 1 point."}
{"id": "2026", "revid": "27868532", "url": "https://divinity.fandom.com/wiki?curid=2026", "title": "Dragon Knight Saga Characters", "text": "\nThere are two types of Characters in Divinity; The Main Character: Who is the person you play as, and Non-Playable Characters (NPCs): Who are people in the game that you cannot control. \nYou can talk to some of these characters, and depending on your dialog choices, they can open up &lt;a href=\"Divinity%20II%20quests\"&gt;quests&lt;/a&gt; and lead to &lt;a href=\"exp\"&gt;exp&lt;/a&gt;erience or &lt;a href=\"Items%20%28Dragon%20Knight%20Saga%29\"&gt;items&lt;/a&gt; as rewards.\nAt the left of the dialog it may also be possible to &lt;a href=\"mindread\"&gt;mindread&lt;/a&gt; the character to learn addition information.\nIn Divinity II, your main character can summon their own &lt;a href=\"The%20Creature\"&gt;creature&lt;/a&gt; with the &lt;a href=\"Crystal%20Skull\"&gt;Crystal Skull&lt;/a&gt;.\nContinuing with an Existing Character.\nIf you want to continue your adventure with an existing character, all you have to do is load a save game from \"\" and proceed to the end of the game. After the finale, Flames of Vengeance will automatically begin.\nStarting with a New Character.\nWhen you want to start playing Flames of Vengeance with a new character, you will have the option of choosing either a preset or a custom hero after having selected his/her looks. \nThis will be a level 35 character that begins the new journey with an ample amount of gold to compensate for the lack of previously acquired gear.\n\u201cPreset\u201d means that you take you pick from among four developer-designed classes. These are: the Warrior, a melee specialist; the Mage, a magic specialist; the Ranger, a ranged specialist and the Priest, a summoning specialist. Choosing any one of these will skip all further customisation and immediately trigger the start of Flames of Vengeance.\nAlternatively, you can opt for Advanced Customisation during which you build a brand new, level 35 character from the ground up. You can also however, still select one of the presets which you can then tweak and adjust as you see fit. \nIt is important to note that when choosing skills during this process of character creation, you can maximize the ones you like here and now, but when starting the game the rest will have their normal skill caps again. Your &lt;a href=\"Skill%20Trainer\"&gt;skill trainers&lt;/a&gt; can remedy that of course!"}
