{"id": "5901", "revid": "31775388", "url": "https://divinity.fandom.com/wiki?curid=5901", "title": "Secrets of the Scroll", "text": "I\nSpecial: Dust To Dust\nOne of the major ingredients the aspiring enchanter and poion-mixer should master is bone dust. In this case, success depends on the proper use of tools. A morter and pestle will always produce a fine-grain bone dust, whereas more redumentary or aggressive methods of grinding bones and skulls will leav you with a pile of useless splinters. Invest in a mortar and pestle before considering a cheap alternative. Pile after pile of fine and effective bone dust will be your reward for this small investment!\nII\nSpecial: Dust to Dust\nPixie dust is to enchanting as kindling is to fire: one is the basis of the other. But never fear! You needn't go pixie-hunting and pixie-crushing unless you've scads of spare time and an iron stomach. No, first we begin with stardust. Fortunatlely, you needn't carve and crush a chuck from a constellation (unless again, you've the time and stomach). The stardust herb is relatively common and simply to crush to a fine powder. Combines with bonedust, you've a very powerful pixie dust indeed!\nBut let's not leave the oft-forgotten moondust out of the equation! I won't bore you with the details, but suffice it to say a simple moonstone gem will suffice as fully as a chunk of the moon itself. Combine crushed moonstone (moondust) with stardust to create a fine pixie dust!\nIII\nRivellon's powers are many, and even without the intervention of we enchanters, her magic shines through even the most common objects. Sprinkled with a bit of pixie dust, these objects' natural powers are quite enhanced! A rabbit's paw, for instance, might only be of use to the most superstitious, but given a fine coating of pixie dust, the paw's magical properties spring to life! Held on a thread, rope, or ring the magical paw will bring great luck to its wearer.\nBut the rabbit's paw is only the tip of the magical iceber...\nIV\nA gifted mage is also a calligrapher and an author, composing his own scrolls and even skillbooks. Before a magical book is procured however, an appropriate pot of ink and quill enchanted with pixie dust must be obtained. If you can't find a quill, A whittled feather does the job!\nV\nA fish can'tlive in the sky, and a magic spell can't live on mundane paper! Enchant paper with pixie dust to make a setting suitable for the magic that will flow through you. Once you've set magical quill to magical paper, allow your spirits to guide you. Surprise is magic's most endearing element, after all!\nVI\nIf you find yourself in need of a sheet of paper while wandering the wilds (or a village of illiterates), you can easily create your own. Find some scraps of wood, dampen them, then fire them to create a perfectly useful leaf.\nVII\nThey say Sire Brihtsturm had a magical weapon. The tale goes that Sir Brightsturm himself had imbued it with the tormented soul of a ghost. How he would go about that, no one may ever know, but it did make him hit harder, and he could sense when and where strikes and arrows were going to land. Unfortunately, successful though Sir Brightsturm may have been, the magic could not save his life. On the contrary: it had one drawback. Wielding the sword made his body carry a heavy burden, and as soon as he would leave the battlefield, he would appear and old, worn down man. Tired, sickly. Strong as he may have been, his body one day couldn't take it anymore, and he died a young man in an old body.\nVIII\nFacing elementas is a nasty business, but luckily for the adventurous enchanter, their magical essence can imbue countless objects with the power of the elements!\nIX\nRubies are precious gems indeed, and humaniy's best friend against the harmful effects of weather and climate. Infusedin one's equipment, they can protect and adventurer through the direct landscapes, rom dry deserts to freezing tundra.\nX\nA blank book is an empty pot: its virtues ought not to be judged by what it lacks. The adept master of either is responsible for filling the former with a magical scroll adn the latter with meat and vegetables."}
{"id": "16859", "revid": "43671602", "url": "https://divinity.fandom.com/wiki?curid=16859", "title": "Seed of Power", "text": " is a &lt;a href=\"Original%20Sin%202%20Quests\"&gt;Relics of Rivellon side quest&lt;/a&gt; in \"\".\nDetailed walkthrough.\nUpon boarding the ship in the hidden alcove, head to the ship's bow where the &lt;a href=\"elf\"&gt;elf&lt;/a&gt; Daeyena can be found surrounded by magister guards being led by &lt;a href=\"Krendt\"&gt;Krendt&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Ellwin\"&gt;Ellwin&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Swentin\"&gt;Swentin&lt;/a&gt;. If the party is led by an elf, they will recognise Daeyena as a &lt;a href=\"Scion\"&gt;Scion&lt;/a&gt; and have the option to inform the Magisters of your obligation to protect the Scion. Either attempt to keep out of the situation or come to the elf's aid; regardless of the choice made, battle will ensue and the Magisters must be defeated.\nOnce the Magisters are defeated, Daeyena will speak to the &lt;a href=\"Godwoken\"&gt;Godwoken&lt;/a&gt; and explain she is trying to retrieve the spores that were stolen from her, otherwise she will walk off. Head to the ship's stern to find the &lt;a href=\"Ship%27s%20Manifesto\"&gt;manifest&lt;/a&gt; and spore container, the latter directly beside a dead magister on the elevated part of the ship (you may have to spin the camera to see it). Take the container and read the manifest.\nIf Daeyena dies in Act 1, you can retrieve the first two pieces of the Armour of Contamination (the &lt;a href=\"Boots%20of%20Contamination\"&gt;Boots of Contamination&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Greaves%20of%20Contamination\"&gt;Greaves of Contamination&lt;/a&gt; ), but you can still retrieve them later if she survives. To retreive all of the pieces, you have to kill her at some point, and the boots and leggings she has on her will be leveled to whatever level she was when you killed her.\nAssuming she survived Act 1, Daeyena can be found again in Act 2, on the road by the &lt;a href=\"Elven%20Encampment\"&gt;Elven Encampment&lt;/a&gt;, the &lt;a href=\"A%20Trial%20for%20All%20Seasons\"&gt;A Trial for All Seasons&lt;/a&gt;, and the Magicockerel. There, she has a magister prisoner, and if spoken to, she will execute said prisoner. This creates the third piece, the gauntlets. You can kill her for the three pieces now (two level 14 elves, a hidden tree monster, and two hidden plant summons, also at level 14. The other elf has Provoke), but, again, if you let her live you can still retrieve them in &lt;a href=\"Arx\"&gt;Arx&lt;/a&gt; (Note: if you fight her her before the execution, you can use &lt;a href=\"Trigger%20Spores\"&gt;Trigger Spores&lt;/a&gt; to make the gauntlets yourself -- this kills the magister). The gauntlets will be made at YOUR level, not Daeyena's.\nIf however Daeyena managed to die on the ship in Fort Joy, you must use the \"Contamination Spore\" (not flawed) as fuel to activate the skill \"Trigger Spores\" to kill a magister. Note that the skill is blocked by magic armor, so be sure to peel it off the target first. This will give the character that used \"Trigger Spores\" an effect that generates the gauntlets upon their death (so have that resurrection scroll ready). \n\"Trigger Spores\" can be obtained from eating the flesh Daeyena drops upon her death or alternatively by reading the Spore Research Notes on a stool in the North East of the Blackpit, next to the contaminated elf.\nThe chest piece can be found in the exterior of &lt;a href=\"the%20Blackpits\"&gt;the Blackpits&lt;/a&gt;, afflicting a magister. The magister is on an upper area that loops back from the oil derrick. You can hear this magister in conversation before entering the blackpits itself, by the gates. A speech check aids in the removal of the armour, otherwise you can kill the magister. You can return the chest piece to Daeyena, or keep it (or bring it to her but then refuse to give it to her, causing a fight). \nShould Daeyena survive Act 2, you can retrieve the rest of the pieces of the set in Arx, in the magical research room in Reimond's basement. To acquire all the pieces requires killing her now, or they are gone. The helmet is essentially cursed, afflicting the wearer with \"permanent\" &lt;a href=\"Mad%20%28Status%29\"&gt;Madness&lt;/a&gt;. A speech check can be made to avoid this effect (difficulty 5). If the cursed helmet is worn, it can only be removed upon the character's death."}
